  "prompt": "Why does lodha panel interfere in BCCI?",
  "response": "The **Lodha Committee** was formed by the **Supreme Court of India** in January 2015 to address issues of **corruption, mismanagement, and lack of transparency** in the **Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI)**. The committee was headed by former Chief Justice of India, **Justice R.M. Lodha**, and was tasked with recommending reforms to ensure **good governance, accountability, and professionalism** in the BCCI.\n\nHere\u2019s why the Lodha Committee intervened in the BCCI:\n\n1. **2013 IPL Spot-Fixing Scandal**:\n   - The IPL spot-fixing scandal exposed **deep-rooted corruption** in Indian cricket, involving players, officials, and bookies.\n   - This led to a loss of public trust in the BCCI, prompting the Supreme Court to step in.\n\n2. **Lack of Transparency and Accountability**:\n   - The BCCI was criticized for operating like a **private club**, with little transparency in its decision-making processes.\n   - There were concerns about **conflict of interest**, nepotism, and misuse of power by officials.\n\n3. **Conflict of Interest Issues**:\n   - Many BCCI officials held multiple roles in cricket administration and other related businesses, leading to **conflicts of interest**.\n   - This raised questions about the impartiality and fairness of decision-making.\n\n4. **Supreme Court\u2019s Directive**:\n   - Following the IPL scandal, the Supreme Court appointed the Lodha Committee to investigate the affairs of the BCCI and recommend reforms.\n   - The committee was given the authority to suggest structural and operational changes to bring **accountability and transparency** to cricket administration.\n\n5. **Recommendations by the Lodha Committee**:\n   - The committee submitted its report in January 2016, proposing sweeping reforms, including:\n     - **Age and tenure limits** for office bearers.\n     - **One state, one vote** policy to ensure fair representation.\n     - Restrictions on **conflict of interest**.\n     - Greater **transparency** in financial dealings.\n   - The Supreme Court approved most of these recommendations and directed the BCCI to implement them.\n\n6. **Resistance from BCCI**:\n   - The BCCI initially resisted implementing the reforms, leading to further court interventions and eventual compliance.\n\nIn summary, the Lodha Committee intervened in the BCCI to address **corruption, lack of transparency, and poor governance**, with the aim of restoring public trust and ensuring the better management of cricket in India.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
